{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01QC9S6eejipndp2kT8knAyv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01UqjUT1XtDx3BRi6xR4nHnX","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n elasticsearch create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'AUDIT_EOF'\n================================================================\nELASTICSEARCH CLUSTER SECURITY & COMPLIANCE AUDIT\nCluster: es-cluster  |  Date: 2026-06-24  |  Version: 8.11.1\n================================================================\n\nEXECUTIVE SUMMARY\n-----------------\n5 nodes (3 master-eligible / 2 dedicated data), 2 user indices.\nMandatory controls (TLS, authentication) are active. Several\nhardening gaps require remediation.\n\nSEVERITY LEGEND: [CRITICAL] [HIGH] [MEDIUM] [LOW] [INFO]\n\n================================================================\n1. TLS / ENCRYPTION IN TRANSIT\n================================================================\n\n[INFO] HTTP TLS enabled (xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: true).\n       All REST API traffic is encrypted; plaintext HTTP refused.\n\n[INFO] Transport TLS enabled (xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled:\n       true). Inter-node communication is encrypted.\n\n[HIGH] Transport SSL verification_mode is \"certificate\" on ALL nodes\n       (es-config and es-data-config ConfigMaps). This verifies that\n       the peer certificate is signed by the trusted CA but does NOT\n       verify the hostname/CN. Recommended value is \"full\" to prevent\n       a compromised node inside the trust boundary from impersonating\n       another node.\n       Setting: xpack.security.transport.ssl.verification_mode: certificate\n       Fix: change to verification_mode: full\n\n[MEDIUM] No explicit TLS protocol version or cipher suite restrictions\n         are configured. Elasticsearch 8.x defaults to TLS 1.2/1.3\n         but explicitly setting ssl.supported_protocols and\n         ssl.cipher_suites is recommended for FIPS/compliance postures.\n\n[INFO] Self-signed CA in use (CN=es-ca). CA and server cert issued\n       2026-06-24, expire 2027-06-24 (1 year). No OCSP/CRL revocation\n       capability. CA is NOT integrated with an enterprise PKI.\n\n[INFO] Server cert SAN: DNS:localhost, DNS:*.elasticsearch.svc,\n       DNS:*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local\n       Key: RSA-2048, Signature: SHA-256 — acceptable minimums.\n\n[LOW] HTTP compression is disabled (http.compression: false, non-\n      default). This avoids BREACH-class attacks on HTTPS but has a\n      latency/bandwidth trade-off; document the intentional choice.\n\n================================================================\n2. AUTHENTICATION & AUTHORIZATION\n================================================================\n\n[INFO] xpack.security.enabled: true on all nodes. Anonymous access\n       confirmed blocked (401 returned on unauthenticated requests).\n\n[INFO] xpack.security.enrollment.enabled: false — enrollment API\n       disabled, reducing attack surface for unauthorized node joins.\n\n[HIGH] The built-in \"elastic\" superuser account is enabled with a\n       static password stored in Kubernetes Secret \"elastic-password\".\n       The elastic superuser should be used only for bootstrap; a\n       dedicated named admin account should replace it for day-to-day\n       operations, and the elastic account password should be\n       rotated/vaulted, not persisted in a plaintext-equivalent Secret.\n\n[HIGH] Custom file-realm user \"ops-user\" is mapped to the built-in\n       \"superuser\" role (unrestricted cluster + all-index privileges).\n       Principle of least privilege requires this account to hold only\n       the specific cluster/index privileges it needs.\n\n[MEDIUM] Multiple built-in system accounts are enabled but their\n         corresponding services appear absent from the cluster:\n           kibana, kibana_system — no Kibana deployment observed\n           logstash_system       — no Logstash deployment observed\n           beats_system          — no Beats deployment observed\n           apm_system            — no APM server observed\n         Unused accounts with assigned roles increase the attack\n         surface. Disable accounts for services not in use.\n\n[INFO] \"report-user\" is mapped to the built-in \"viewer\" role\n       (read-only). Appropriate scope.\n\n[INFO] Passwords in file realm are bcrypt-hashed (cost factor $2a$10).\n       Hash values are stored in Kubernetes Secret\n       \"es-file-realm-aggregate\" (base64, not encrypted at rest unless\n       the cluster has Secret encryption enabled).\n\n[INFO] No API keys are active.\n[INFO] No role mappings are configured (external IdP/SAML not in use).\n[INFO] No custom application privileges defined.\n\n================================================================\n3. AUDIT LOGGING\n================================================================\n\n[CRITICAL] Security audit logging is NOT enabled.\n           xpack.security.audit.enabled is absent from elasticsearch.yml\n           on all nodes. In Elasticsearch 8.x, audit logging is off by\n           default; the setting must be explicitly enabled.\n           The log4j2 config contains an audit appender but it is\n           inactive. Without audit logging, authentication failures,\n           privilege escalations, and data-access events are not\n           recorded, making forensic analysis and compliance reporting\n           impossible.\n           Fix: add to elasticsearch.yml:\n             xpack.security.audit.enabled: true\n             xpack.security.audit.logfile.events.include: >\n               ACCESS_DENIED,AUTHENTICATION_FAILED,\n               TAMPERED_REQUEST,CONNECTION_DENIED\n\n================================================================\n4. NETWORK EXPOSURE & KUBERNETES NETWORK POLICY\n================================================================\n\n[CRITICAL] No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy exists in the elasticsearch\n           namespace. Any pod cluster-wide can reach port 9200 (REST)\n           and port 9300 (transport). NetworkPolicy should restrict:\n           - Ingress to 9200: only authorized client namespaces/pods\n           - Ingress to 9300: only pods in the elasticsearch namespace\n           - All other ingress: denied\n\n[MEDIUM] network.host: \"0.0.0.0\" — nodes listen on all interfaces.\n         Binding to the pod IP (network.host: _site_) would limit\n         exposure within the pod network.\n\n[INFO] Service \"es-http\" is ClusterIP (not LoadBalancer/NodePort).\n       Not externally reachable by default.\n[INFO] Service \"es-transport\" is headless ClusterIP. Not externally\n       reachable.\n\n================================================================\n5. CLUSTER SETTINGS\n================================================================\n\n[MEDIUM] action.auto_create_index: true (default). Automatic index\n         creation is active; any client can create new indices by\n         writing to a non-existent index name. Restrict to a pattern\n         allowlist or set to false to prevent data sprawl and\n         accidental schema drift.\n         Example fix:\n           action.auto_create_index: \".monitoring-*,.watches,.triggered_watches,.watcher-history-*,.ml-*\"\n\n[INFO] action.destructive_requires_name: true (default, good).\n       Wildcard index deletion is blocked.\n\n[MEDIUM] bootstrap.memory_lock: false (default). Elasticsearch heap\n         can be swapped to disk, risking performance degradation and\n         potential exposure of sensitive data in swap. Set to true and\n         ensure the OS/container ulimit permits it.\n\n[INFO] No persistent or transient cluster settings have been modified\n       from defaults (persistent: {}, transient: {}).\n\n[INFO] cluster.max_shards_per_node: 1000 (default). Acceptable for\n       current scale (3 user shards across 5 nodes).\n\n================================================================\n6. INDEX CONFIGURATION & SECURITY\n================================================================\n\nINDEX: test-index\n  Shards: 1 primary, 1 replica  |  Docs: 1  |  Size: ~10KB\n  Zone allocation: none (index.routing.allocation.include._tier_preference:\n    data_content — shards may land on any data-capable node)\n  ILM policy: none\n  [MEDIUM] No ILM policy — no automated retention, rollover, or\n           deletion. Data will accumulate indefinitely.\n\nINDEX: app-data\n  Shards: 2 primary, 1 replica  |  Docs: 0  |  Size: ~1KB\n  Zone allocation: index.routing.allocation.require.zone: new\n    (shards pinned exclusively to es-data-0 and es-data-1)\n  ILM policy: none\n  [INFO] Zone-pinning is intentional per observed configuration.\n         Verify the \"new\" zone nodes (es-data-0, es-data-1) have\n         sufficient capacity; if they become unavailable, shards cannot\n         rebalance to \"original\" zone nodes.\n  [MEDIUM] No ILM policy — same retention concern as test-index.\n\n[MEDIUM] No index-level security (field-level security, document-level\n         security, or index aliases with filters) is configured.\n         Sensitive data is accessible to any user with index read\n         privileges.\n\n================================================================\n7. NODE ROLES & CLUSTER TOPOLOGY\n================================================================\n\n[HIGH] Master-eligible nodes (es-0, es-1, es-2) also hold data,\n       ingest, ML, and transform roles. In a production hardened\n       deployment, dedicated master nodes should hold only the master\n       role to protect quorum stability and reduce the blast radius of\n       a data-node compromise.\n       Current roles on es-0/es-1/es-2:\n         master, data, data_cold, data_content, data_frozen, data_hot,\n         data_warm, ingest, ml, remote_cluster_client, transform\n\n[INFO] Dedicated data nodes es-data-0 and es-data-1 correctly carry\n       only the \"data\" role and are zone-attributed as \"new\".\n\n================================================================\n8. POD SECURITY (KUBERNETES)\n================================================================\n\n[MEDIUM] Pods run as UID 1000, fsGroup 1000 — non-root, good.\n         However, the securityContext does NOT explicitly set:\n           runAsNonRoot: true\n           allowPrivilegeEscalation: false\n           readOnlyRootFilesystem: true\n           capabilities: {drop: [ALL]}\n         Without these, a container escape or misconfiguration could\n         gain unintended capabilities.\n\n[LOW] StatefulSets do not specify imagePullPolicy: Always for the\n      es-data StatefulSet (imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent). A stale\n      cached image could be used if the tag is mutable.\n\n================================================================\n9. SECRET MANAGEMENT\n================================================================\n\n[MEDIUM] The TLS private key (es-http-tls) and elastic user password\n         (elastic-password) are stored as Kubernetes Secrets. Secrets\n         are only base64-encoded by default; without Secret encryption\n         at rest configured on the cluster's etcd, these are readable\n         by anyone with etcd or Secret read access.\n         Recommendation: enable etcd encryption at rest and/or use an\n         external secrets manager (Vault, AWS Secrets Manager, etc.).\n\n[LOW] TLS certificate private key is shared across all nodes (same\n      Secret mounted into every pod). A per-node certificate is\n      preferred to limit the impact of a key compromise.\n\n================================================================\n10. BACKUP & RECOVERY\n================================================================\n\n[HIGH] No snapshot repositories are configured. There is no backup\n       strategy for cluster data. A single point of failure (e.g.,\n       accidental index deletion or storage corruption) cannot be\n       recovered. Configure at least one repository and an SLM\n       (Snapshot Lifecycle Management) policy.\n\n================================================================\n11. VERSION & PATCH POSTURE\n================================================================\n\n[HIGH] Elasticsearch version is 8.11.1 (build 6f9ff581, released\n       ~Nov 2023). As of audit date 2026-06-24, this is approximately\n       30 months behind the 8.x release train. Multiple security\n       advisories and bug fixes have been released since 8.11.1.\n       Upgrade to the latest stable 8.x release (or 9.x if\n       applicable) on a scheduled maintenance window.\n\n================================================================\nFINDINGS SUMMARY\n================================================================\n\nSeverity   Count  Items\n---------  -----  -----------------------------------------------\nCRITICAL       2  Audit logging disabled; no NetworkPolicy\nHIGH           5  Transport SSL verification_mode; elastic superuser\n                  exposed; ops-user over-privileged; mixed node roles;\n                  no snapshots; outdated version (8.11.1)\nMEDIUM         8  Cipher/protocol not restricted; unused system users;\n                  auto_create_index enabled; memory_lock off; no ILM;\n                  no index-level security; pod securityContext gaps;\n                  Secrets not encrypted at rest\nLOW            3  http.compression setting; imagePullPolicy; shared TLS key\n\nAll live settings were observed READ-ONLY. No changes were made.\n================================================================\nAUDIT_EOF\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap with security findings"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1152,"cache_read_input_tokens":54093,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1152},"output_tokens":31,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c7d4eb4f-81c0-491f-a9da-66d70a3e54df","uuid":"6749af29-9385-411b-9377-7654fc04482b","request_id":"req_011CcN2N26EEW5YZACW9ZHLC"}
